Camille Auer wanted to correct her gender, was diagnosed as mentally ill and now she makes art on the subject - &quot;A person should have the right to their own body&quot;
Dozens of patient reports hang from the ceiling of the Academy of Fine Arts&#39; Project room gallery.
Camille Auer&#39;s name is written on each of them.
The papers tell the multi-year story of how outsiders have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
Decided for him who he is.
&quot;I wanted to tell my personal treatment history to make the violence of the process visible,&quot; says Auer.
By process, he refers to the gender reassignment process.
It is often a research period lasting years, which includes meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process starts with a referral to diagnostic tests for &quot;gender identity disorder&quot;, which are carried out in Tampere and Helsinki.
For Auer, the process started four years ago.
Even before this, she had used estrogen she had ordered via the internet and was already very far along in her own repair process.
She thought she was a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must go through the correction process in order to legally correct their gender.
The Trans Act, i.e. the law on confirming the gender of transsexuals (563/2002), obliges transgender people to undergo forced sterilization in order to obtain the correct gender in, for example, the population registry center and passport.
At the moment, a psychiatric diagnosis and a certificate of infertility are required from everyone undergoing gender reassignment.
A person has the right to decide about his own body.
&quot;This situation is intolerable and violates human rights,&quot; says Auer.
There has been talk about reforming the Translaw in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has issued eight observations on the law and the European Court of Human Rights has a preliminary ruling that obliges the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to observe the right to self-determination.
Finland&#39;s previous government prepared the amendment of the law under the leadership of the then Minister of Social Affairs and Health, Susanne Huovinen.
Elections came and the Basic Finns took over the government.
Now the law change is stuck again.
These are internal political disputes that are not even related to this law in question.
&quot;The government does not want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the government about changing the law,&quot; says Frank Johansson, executive director of Amnesty&#39;s Finnish department.
The front of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of them consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the medicines used by Auer.
In the Patient Narrative installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of Auer by the transpol psychologist at Tampere University Hospital.
The psychologist met Camille Auer twice and based on these, wrote a report that would define Auer&#39;s right to receive treatment and help.
The subject&#39;s sense of reality appears to be susceptible to wavering.
The subject&#39;s self-perception appears fragmented in a borderline-like manner, and the unstable features related to personality are highlighted.
Auer did not recognize himself from these descriptions.
&quot;It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed as mentally ill,&quot; says Auer.
An even bigger shock was when Auer was not granted gender reassignment treatment.
According to the nursing staff, his resources were not sufficient to start the process.
He was denied his own identity.
That&#39;s when, on February 11, 2015, Auer walked out of a meeting and kicked the television in the waiting room of the transpol.
Later, from that television came an artwork called Monument for the Excluded, in which Auer reflects on his experience of power and its use.
&quot;It&#39;s crazy that anyone defined as female at birth can enlarge their breasts, but to remove them you need a diagnosis,&quot; says Auer.
Your body is not yours if you feel that you are something other than the sex assigned to you at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer&#39;s experience is not the only one of its kind.
For many, the gender reassignment process is more difficult for spiritual reasons than for purely medical operations.
Those who go through it meet dozens of people to whom they have to justify their own existence and their right to their own gender experience.
&quot;It&#39;s crazy that people who are in need of support and help are denied treatment on the grounds that they don&#39;t have enough resources,&quot; says Auer.
Many of those who applied for the process have psychological symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, possible experiences of bullying.
Referring to these, the medical staff can order that the treatment cannot be started.
&quot;Preventing getting treatment and help can put a person in an even worse situation than they were before starting the process,&quot; says Auer.
Auer&#39;s personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts of suicide.
In the text of the exhibition publication, Auer writes: &quot;I&#39;ve had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life and that&#39;s something that people usually have a hard time digesting.&quot;
Depression has been treated with medication and when Auer started using hormones, he felt better.
He had finally been able to put into words the feelings that had already existed in childhood and adolescence.
Why a wide chin didn&#39;t seem to fit my body and why the pectoral muscles had to be round instead of a flat chest.
The most important thing for Auer has been that there are people near him who see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
&quot;You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing, using your voice and movements,&quot; he says.
Today, Auer already feels that she will be seen, she exists as a woman.
However, in the early stages of the process, random comments from loved ones could hurt a lot.
It hurts the most when loved ones misgender.
&quot;They should know and they know who I am, but they won&#39;t or can&#39;t internalize it,&quot; he continues.
However, not all trans people need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body hysphoria, i.e. body discord, where the body or its parts can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without using hormones and a long research process, you cannot get official confirmation of your own gender.
&quot;There is absolutely no medical basis for these studies,&quot; says Auer.
And it&#39;s true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014, the parliament approved a new procedure for recognizing legal gender.
The new legislation is based on the right to self-determination regarding legal gender.
An adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identification number, stating that he/she feels that he/she is of the other gender.
After the six-month consideration period, the applicant confirms his application in writing and the ministry issues the applicant with a new personal identification number.
This right to self-determination is demanded in Finland as well, and Auer&#39;s exhibition also encapsulates this demand.
It has not been a therapy experience for the artist, but the exhibition is a collection of political and artistic works.
I want to believe that art still has weight and that it can be used to bring about political changes in a time when politicians have forgotten human rights.
Camille Auer&#39;s exhibition Antiphallic Dick 4-28 July 2017 at the Academy of Fine Arts&#39; Project Room.
A civil rights organization issued a travel warning for Missouri
The NAACP, a national organization that advocates for African-American civil rights, has issued a travel warning for Missouri. The reason is the discriminatory practices of the state and the racist attacks that happened there.
&quot;The NAACP Travel Advisory for Missouri, effective August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors and locals to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling in a state that has recently experienced numerous questionable racial incidents,&quot; the organization&#39;s release states.
A law recently enacted in Missouri makes it more difficult to take discrimination cases to court. Additionally, state law enforcement disproportionately targets minorities. According to the NAACP, these factors led to the issuance of the travel warning.
&quot;People&#39;s civil rights are being violated.
They are stopped and beaten or killed because of the color of their skin,” NAACP Missouri President Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
&quot;We have never heard of so many cases in such a short time before.&quot;
The travel advisory for Missouri is the organization&#39;s first warning for a US state.
The organization cited as examples the racist comments made against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year. He was driving across the state when his car ran out of gas. Missouri police arrested him, although he was not charged with a crime.
The travel bulletin also referred to a study by the Missouri Attorney General, according to which the police are 75 percent more likely to stop a black driver than a white one.
&quot;The purpose of the travel advisory is to tell people to be on the lookout and to warn their families, friends and co-workers about what could happen in Missouri,&quot; says Chapel.
&quot;People need to prepare by, for example, bringing money to pay bail or telling relatives they plan to travel across the state.&quot;
According to the FBI, 100 hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, which is the 16th highest number of US states.
The travel warning is also a response to Missouri&#39;s new law that makes it harder to sue companies for discrimination in housing and employment.
The ACLU, which defends constitutional civil rights, recently issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after they passed immigration laws that require police to arrest people for immigration violations. According to the organization, this increases racial profiling.
Generally, travel warnings are published by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and they apply to other countries. Recently, however, NGOs have published them in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
