The sanctions immediately intensified the talks
Until a while ago, it seemed that relations between the United States and Russia were on the way from cold to warm.
US President Donald Trump and Russian President Vladimir Putin, who met in connection with the G20 meeting of industrialized countries in Hamburg, seemed to get along perfectly well.
Since then, the atmosphere has cooled considerably.
Russia reacted bitterly to the new economic sanctions approved by the US Congress last week and signed by Trump on Wednesday.
The most shocking answer so far has been heard from Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev, according to whom the sanctions law signed by Trump means a &quot;full-scale trade war&quot;.
Even if the Russian reactions are dismissed only as escalations and excesses belonging to political rhetoric, the tension between the United States and Russia is a fact after the short honeymoon period after Trump&#39;s election.
In the United States, the passage of the sanctions law concerning Russia, Iran and North Korea was not simple.
Although Congress passed the law with considerable unanimity, it was reportedly much more difficult for the president to pass the law.
Trump criticized the law he had just signed as &quot;significantly flawed&quot;.
Russia in particular must have been the reason for President Trump&#39;s grumpiness, although the approval of a law limiting his own powers must also have been repulsive.
As is well known, there is an investigation in the United States into Russia&#39;s possible interference in the presidential election as well as the Trump campaign&#39;s connections to Russia.
The tension between the United States and Russia is a fact after a short honeymoon.
When the staff of the White House has changed rapidly and various scandalous twists and turns have been revealed almost without update, it seems increasingly clear that foreign policy in the United States is not made under the leadership of the president, but in spite of the president.
Such a situation is by no means desirable.
If the relationship with Russia is a mess in the United States, the same applies to the European Union.
In addition to economic sanctions, the tense security situation in the Union&#39;s core area in the Baltic Sea is also straining relations.
The EU has visibly highlighted Ukraine&#39;s situation in its relations with Russia and demanded the implementation of the Minsk Agreement.
Although the Union has so far remained unified in its Russia policy, at least on the surface, the interests of the member countries are quite different.
For a member country like Finland that trades a lot with Russia, economic sanctions have been a real problem.
The effects of the recent sanctions law in the United States are still unclear.
It has been feared in the EU that the sanctions will make it difficult for many European companies to operate.
In Finland, the effects may be felt, for example, in the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project and possibly in the Fennovoima nuclear power plant project.
Acidity in Europe has been caused by the fact that, for example, liquefied natural gas lng, which is important to the US economy, has been left out of the sanctions.
Trade sanctions are a way in world politics to show disapproval.
However, economic sanctions must be well thought out and carefully considered.
Otherwise, they easily do more harm than good.
Is nothing sacred anymore?
Trump&#39;s White House now has the Statue of Liberty in its sights
Tampering with the statues is the surest sign of a change of power.
Americans know it as well as anyone: Iraqis, together with American soldiers, toppled the statue of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the main ideologues of the Trump administration, knew very well what he was doing in a heated debate with CNN&#39;s Jim Acosta. The Statue of Liberty came under Miller&#39;s attack in a barrage of words about the president&#39;s proposal to greatly reduce legal immigration.
Miller didn&#39;t really criticize the statue itself.
Had he done so, he would have been attacked by huge hordes of cruise operators and Statue of Liberty impersonators.
The object of his attack was the meaning of the statue and especially the fact that in 1903 a poem by Emma Lazarus was added to the pedestal of the statue - 17 years after the statue was completed.
This is how Miller put Acosta: &quot;I don&#39;t want to go into history in more detail now, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that lights up the whole world.
The poem was added later and does not belong in the original Statue of Liberty.&quot;
Miller wasn&#39;t wrong per se, but it&#39;s not all about history, as he himself said.
What is essential are Lazarus&#39; touching words, the only ones of their kind in which the state does not invite only immigrants but &quot;the poorest of the poor&quot;: &quot;Your tired, your poor, / Your huddled masses yearning to Breathe free, / The Wretched refuse of your teeming shore.&quot;
The poem is now more relevant than ever.
Miller was by no means practicing literary criticism. He made it clear that the &quot;poorest of the poor&quot; are not welcome in Trump&#39;s United States.
The controversy over the meaning of the Statue of Liberty is part of a larger political and cultural controversy over the meaning of the United States.
Friends of Lazarus campaigned after his death to have the poem affixed to the statue&#39;s pedestal. They were well aware that the act was strongly political.
The purpose of the statue was to embody the connections between French and American republicanism with a classical metaphor, the feminine embodiment of freedom.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in his poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, but has a voice.
And it gives itself a new name: the mother of the deportees.
Attaching the poem to the image was a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on the American idea of nationhood.
Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, and the right has long wanted to change it back to the original.
Rush Limbaugh — a mouthpiece that can now be seen as something of a Trump harbinger — claimed in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty is not an invitation to anyone, but an early pioneer of neoconservatives, carrying America&#39;s torch into a world shrouded in darkness: “Lady Liberty steps forth.
He takes the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch does not show the way to the United States.”
Rarely, Limbaugh was partially right.
The meaning of the Statue of Liberty depends entirely on perspective.
Lazarus saw it like the poor and exhausted but hopeful immigrants from the deck of a ship after a long and trying journey.
He saw it from the perspective of people seeking shelter and a better life.
His Statue of Liberty comforts by giving hope and welcoming.
And that&#39;s definitely not what Miller and Trump want.
Their torch does not show the way but fan the flames of anger, their only source of power.
