Blocking critics on Facebook: Don&#39;t run for public office if you can&#39;t handle criticism
The father of our country knew what bad publicity was.
Americans loved George Washington, but newspapers soon began criticizing him for everything from his domestic policies to his political principles.
Criticism must have irritated me,
but he did not silence his critics.
“If freedom of speech be taken away, we may be led as dumb and silent as sheep to the slaughter,” Washington said in 1783.
Which brings us to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should take a lesson from Washington.
Hogan&#39;s staff has removed at least 450 comments from his official Facebook page and blocked those who made them.
The American Civil Liberties Union sued Hogan earlier this week.
His staff consider the challenge unfounded, and the attitude was belittling online as well.
&quot;Who cares? This is just Facebook&quot;, many commented.
But it matters,
especially in Hogan&#39;s case.
Hogan is an incredibly popular Republican governor of a Democratic-controlled state.
He has received the second best evaluations for his activities among 50 governors.
Hogan is not sensitive to heat.
He has led the state steadily and strictly adhered to principles.
He has also skilfully used Facebook as the main channel of communication with his voters and published there a picture of his head bald from chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking users coming to the governor&#39;s Facebook page is unnecessary and even dangerous. The governor&#39;s page is a public and official forum maintained by his staff with tax dollars.
Hogan&#39;s spokeswoman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor&#39;s actions in an interview with the Washington Post. According to him, it was just about moderating the comments.
However, labeling commenters as trolls, spammers or haters is too easy a solution.
The Washington Post interviewed users blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to their elected leaders. They were not trolls, but for example teachers, entrepreneurs and pastors.
They reported that their comments were respectful, considerate and to the point.
The pastor quoted the bible in his comment; he wanted to appeal to Hogan&#39;s Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Maryland was not hostile, but raised the issue of hate crimes.
&quot;I politely commented that I was disappointed that Hogan had not addressed the hate crimes and other recent news,&quot; he wrote in comments to the Washington Post story.
&quot;I also cannot accept that when several people comment on the same issue, they are immediately considered an organized group in some way and ignored as a large group of concerned citizens.&quot;
The governor&#39;s staff called the comments a &quot;focused attack.&quot; Someone else might call them promoting things that are considered important.
In the age of Facebook, it is easy to control communication by blocking a reviewer or deleting a critical comment.
In the old days, staff would have had to be sent to collect and burn newspapers that had published critical editorials, or to arrest and silence protesters.
However, it&#39;s actually the same thing, only digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be accused of shackling Facebook and other social media channels.
Twitter users blocked by President Trump have sued him.
The first major decision on the subject was made last week in Virginia.
According to Alexandria District Court Judge James C. Cacheris, the Loudoun County government violated the First Amendment of the United States Constitution by blocking a voter on Facebook.
And the American Civil Liberties Union went to talk to Kentucky Republican Governor Matt Bevin about the use of Twitter and Facebook.
This shouldn&#39;t be difficult.
In Washington&#39;s time, cheap postage had a similar effect to the internet today.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and anonymous writers plagued Washington.
Even back then there were trolls.
The nom de guerres Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius and Portius wrote letters to newspapers berating Washington&#39;s decisions.
The president&#39;s office was flooded with petitions criticizing the Jay Treaty, a cooperation, trade and maritime agreement between the United States and Britain. This is evident from documents collected by the Papers of George Washington online project.
However, he did not silence his critics.
Freedom of speech, freedom of opinion and freedom of discussion are the cornerstones of our nation.
True leadership means accepting this fact.
Summer feeding of birds should be stopped immediately
Samples have come from about fifty places, and in addition online announcements from a couple or three.
Most of them have come from Southern and Western Finland, but then there are also individual ones from Haapavedi and Seinäjoki, says specialist researcher Marja Isomursu from Evira.
Green finches have died from a parasitic disease called trichomoniasis.
It is caused by a protozoan known scientifically as Trichomonas gallinae.
It has previously been known to attack pigeons, and pigeons in particular.
However, in the 21st century, the disease also began to be observed in finches.
In 2009, it really boomed.
Then trichomonosis caused a big collapse in the Finnish greenfinch population, after which the populations of the species have been on the way to recovery.
There have been sick greenfinches now, but at least not yet on a large scale, says Juha Honkala, Curator of the Central Natural History Museum (Luomus) of the University of Helsinki.
It is to be feared that the previous epidemic of greenfinches will be repeated again if something is not done.
What needs to be done now is a very simple thing that anyone can do: stop summer feeding the birds immediately.
More on that later.
