Poverty and death in the golden land of Indonesia
Bardina Degei does not use heat when cooking.
He rarely uses the pot either.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region in Indonesia&#39;s restive Papua province. When he cooks dinner, he usually puts the sweet potato – locally known as “nota” – directly on the stove.
After half an hour, the charred sweet potato is eaten greedily with bare, unwashed hands.
There is no furniture in Degei&#39;s home. He sits on the muddy dirt floor, where he also usually takes care of his daily chores, such as washing clothes in murky water fetched from a nearby swamp.
The toilet function is provided by a bucket in the roofless room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband&#39;s four wives and is not assigned to tend the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many drink heavily. In addition, there are soldiers to consider.
&quot;No one dares to walk in the village after five in the evening,&quot; says Degei.
This is a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed by Indonesia in 1969. The annexation was preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote in public in front of occupation forces.
A local independence movement opposed to Dutch rule quickly turned its anger on the Jakarta government, which tightly controls the area and prevents foreign journalists and human rights monitors from entering.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua. The eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is remote and in a corner. The journey there starts with a one-and-a-half-hour flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and continues with a stomach-churning five-hour drive in a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
In the town of about 19,000 inhabitants, there are wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, whose corrugated iron roofs have been stained yellow-brown by rust.
Few Indonesians have been here, let alone journalists and foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Mee Pago tribesmen of Papua worshiped the god Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes as well.
&quot;We didn&#39;t have clothes like this,&quot; says Degei. She means her colorful, handwoven wrap headpiece, dark skirt and brightly colored blouse.
&quot;Before, we only had leaves to cover our bodies.&quot;
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia. 28 percent of its residents live below the poverty line, and infant mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it is also the golden land of Indonesia.
Paniai is an upland region roughly the size of New Jersey with a population of 153,000. Only about a hundred kilometers from Paniai is Grasberg, the world&#39;s largest and most profitable gold mine. It is owned by the Freeport McMoran company based in Phoenix, USA.
In 2015, the mine produced $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated 78 billion dollars worth of wood reserves.
For the Papuans, however, these riches bring misery, as they mean the stifling presence of Indonesia&#39;s powerful military.
The New York Times revealed in 2005 that Freeport paid local military personnel and local units of the military nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004. Individual officers were paid up to $150,000.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten this source of income and are being ruthlessly silenced.
According to human rights activists, since 1969, the Indonesian army has killed more than 500,000 Papuans and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, mass killings in the highlands of Papua&#39;s tribes in the 1970s reached the proportions of genocide.
Last year, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the region during peaceful protests.
The Brisbane Archdiocese&#39;s 2016 report, We Will Lose Everything, details the previous year&#39;s atrocities, including extrajudicial executions, torture - rape and electric shocks being particularly popular methods - and relentless attacks on peaceful protests.
&quot;Calculating the number of victims is difficult because there are cases every week,&quot; says Andreas Harsono, Indonesian researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have been tightened as Papua&#39;s natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the province&#39;s 3.5 million inhabitants, 83 percent are Christians, but the demographic structure is changing, as Muslims from Indonesia&#39;s populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi move to the region in the hope of a better livelihood.
Javanese warung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado mixed vegetables in peanut sauce.
It&#39;s hard for locals to compete.
&quot;The immigrants have started selling chicken and vegetables at the market cheaper than the locals,&quot; says 24-year-old Abeth You, who is from Paniai and moved to the provincial capital for work.
&quot;Local women lost their customers.&quot;
In his 2014 election campaign, Indonesian President Joko Widodo – nicknamed Jokowi – promised to address injustices and human rights violations in Papua.
Papua consists of 29 districts and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 districts, including Paniai, on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and locals feel betrayed.
&quot;Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 and expected him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice,&quot; You says.
Paniai experienced some sort of trough only two months after Jokowi&#39;s inauguration in October.
Eleven children were singing Christmas carols by the campfire in Enarotal on December 7, 2014, when two Indonesian soldiers on motorcycles appeared out of the dark.
The frightened children told the soldiers that they should use their headlights.
One of the soldiers did not like the remark. According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, the man returned to the scene with four soldiers.
According to the accounts of the victims and witnesses, the drunken soldiers caught the children and beat them with rifles.
So one of the soldiers fired at the children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, fell into a coma as a result of the abuse.
A couple of hours later, the State Election Commission building located near the scene was set on fire, and the next day things began to happen.
About a thousand Papuans – young men and women and children – gathered on the soccer field in front of the local police station and army command center to demand justice.
They had hunting bows with them for parties, and they started to perform the traditional waita dance of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe, which involves dancing in a circle and imitating birdsong.
Some of the protesters started stoning police and army buildings.
As the atmosphere heated up, the soldiers received an order over the internal radio system: &quot;If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them dead.&quot; The information is based on an official document seen by TIME magazine, which has not been released to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, resident leader of the Kego Koto area, foresaw the situation getting out of hand and asked the crowd to calm down and return to their homes.
No one wanted to listen anymore.
&quot;When I turned around, I was shot in the left wrist,&quot; he told TIME magazine on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn&#39;t know who shot him, but the bullet came from the ranks of the soldiers.
&quot;Several shots were fired in the crowd.&quot;
Alfius Youwi was shot three times. His cousin saw the shootings.
&quot;I ran to him and made sure that it was really him,&quot; Yohanes told TIME magazine sadly. Like many Indonesians, he only uses one name.
&quot;I saw that he was dead... I kissed him.&quot;
Papua Inspector General of Police Yotje Mende told reporters that officers were only &quot;protecting&quot; the police station because it was under attack.
&quot;We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,&quot; Papuan police spokesman Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
&quot;Then it&#39;s a matter of life and death.&quot;
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many were injured.
News of the deaths reached Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an emotional speech in Jayapura, in which he expressed his condolences to the families of the victims and promised that the violence in Papua would be addressed.
&quot;I want the case to be investigated immediately so that it never happens again.&quot;
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he would initiate investigations into human rights violations outside the legal system.
However, he immediately began to retract his words.
&quot;Most of the violations happened a long time ago,
In the 1990s and early 2000s.
The important thing is that we have decided to investigate the violations, but certain processes are needed for that,” he said.
In an interview with TIME magazine in Jakarta on June 5, 2017, Wiranto had already changed his mind. He said he did not intend to start investigations in Papua.
&quot;Everything will be settled in court,&quot; he said.
The UN accuses Wiranto of &quot;crimes against humanity&quot;. The crimes are related to the death of more than a thousand people in East Timor&#39;s bloody independence referendum in 1999. Wiranto told TIME magazine that 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua have already been investigated, including the events in Paniai.
The families of Paniai&#39;s victims react to the claims with dark disbelief.
&quot;I have been interviewed four times in the last three years, but things have not progressed in any way,&quot; says Yohanes.
&quot;I&#39;m already tired of this.&quot;
He says that he still lives in fear, even though it has been years since the incident.
&quot;Yes, I&#39;m afraid,&quot; he says.
&quot;I&#39;m afraid the army will arrest me. I&#39;m afraid I&#39;ll be shot.&quot;
His brother Yacobus confirms that the Panianians do not dare to discuss the event.
He says that the soldiers had abused him when he had helped bury four of the victims.
&quot;Soldiers searched for me after burying the victims,&quot; he says.
The shootings have not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in Paniai&#39;s neighboring district of Deiyai.
One person died and 17 were injured in a clash between villagers and the manager of a construction company, which started when the manager refused to take an unconscious man to the hospital. Children were also among the injured.
The man who needed hospital treatment was 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who had fallen into the water while fishing in a nearby river. He died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers demonstrated at the construction site in front of the company&#39;s office.
According to the police, the villagers pelted stones at the policemen, who responded with warning shots.
According to locals, however, a mobile police unit of the Indonesian paramilitary police opened fire on the crowd, killing one villager.
&quot;We are terrified. We fear retaliation,&quot; says 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being brought in for treatment.
&quot;I&#39;ve been hiding at home for two days.&quot;
Deiyai&#39;s parliament has demanded that the policemen who fired the shots be held accountable and that the mobile police unit be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a problem point for the Indonesian government.
The lack of real development is fueling discontent among the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes who live in Papua&#39;s lush central highlands.
Many have joined the Liberation Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to defend the rights of Papuans through sporadic attacks and kidnappings of Indonesian army soldiers.
Some of OPM&#39;s leaders are from Pania, such as Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
The army has responded to the rebellion by arbitrarily arresting and imprisoning thousands of people in Paniai in the name of &quot;safeguarding national sovereignty&quot;.
Some of those arrested never return.
Among Papuans, Paniai is known as a &quot;sad, forgotten place&quot;.
Poverty breeds discontent.
There is little rice for sale in Enarotali, and even that is too expensive for the locals,
like bread.
People grow their own food: mainly sweet potatoes and some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming is women&#39;s work, and one woman can be responsible for four or five sweet potato fields.
Most of the harvest is for the family, and the rest is sold at the market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost just 10,000 rupees (75 cents).
Over time, the differences in the livelihoods of locals and migrants have grown, and the number of migrants has increased since new routes to Nabire Airport were opened.
Jobs are few, and they usually go to immigrants who are better educated and wealthier than the locals.
Only a few Papuans have enough capital and know-how to run their own company competitively.
&quot;Young people don&#39;t want to stay in the village because there is no work or money here,&quot; says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Remote Papua gets little attention in the world.
In addition, restrictions on international reporting are still strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua despite being granted a rare filming permit. The official reason was the inability to cooperate with local institutions.
According to Phelim Kinen, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, Jokowi has not kept his election promises. He has not increased transparency or promoted development by removing restrictions on reporting.
&quot;Journalists reporting from Indonesia&#39;s troubled easternmost provinces of Papua and West Papua face new risks: visa denial and blacklisting,&quot; Kine said in a statement.
The lack of press freedom means that the Indonesian government is only pressured by Papua&#39;s immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands - called on the UN Human Rights Council to investigate Papua&#39;s &quot;numerous and widespread violations&quot;, including the Paniai shooting scene.
These countries have also traditionally supported the Papuan liberation movement.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir denied the accusations and told reporters in Jakarta that &quot;Indonesia is still a democracy with freedom of the press, so covering up evidence of human rights violations would be difficult.&quot;
Locals want foreign governments to intervene.
When the official Dutch delegation led by Human Rights Ambassador Kees Van Baar visited Jayapura on May 4, 2017, the locals broke their silence and expressed their desire for freedom, says a source who participated in the meeting and remains anonymous.
There are presidential elections in Indonesia in 2019, but Papuans say that they are not likely to vote for Jokowi anymore.
&quot;Jokowi means well, but there are people around him who are involved in the shooting scene in Paniai,&quot; says Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know the situation of the people of Pania: they live under the rule of a greedy and unpredictable army in want and poverty, practically without health care services and educational opportunities.
According to Gobai, the people of Pania, like other Papuans, consider their votes for Jokowi a &quot;debt&quot; that must be repaid.
“They don&#39;t want money. They just want justice,” he says.
Despite the threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting scene once again showed their resistance in a symbolic way: they buried one of the victims on the land opposite the police station and the army post.
They know they may never get justice, but at least they won&#39;t let those responsible forget their crimes.
&quot;My family members were killed,&quot; Yacobus says with his head down.
&quot;What else could we do?&quot;
