In the United States, more than 20 percent of air passengers take prohibited items on board, a survey reveals
A survey of airline passengers reveals that more than 20 percent of travelers in the United States had knowingly or unknowingly taken prohibited items onto planes past the Transportation Security Administration (TSA) checkpoints. At least six percent of passengers had knives or other sharp objects that they did not know were prohibited.
Less than one percent said they only found out later that they had mistakenly transported weapons, ammunition or explosives.
More than a thousand passengers answered the survey, and it was carried out by the charter airline Stratos Jet Charters. The results also reveal that young passengers are more likely to defy the rules than others.
Of the passengers who knowingly violated TSA rules, 19.7 percent were representatives of the Y generation and less than 15 percent belonged to the X generation.
The most common rules were broken by bringing food and liquids onto the plane.
More than three percent admitted to knowingly taking objects with a blade onto the plane. In addition, 2.2 percent of women and 3.7 percent of men said that they knowingly took prohibited medicinal substances on the plane.
Travelers from all over the United States took part in the survey. The company that carried out the survey wanted to find out how many people had accidentally taken contraband goods past the security check and how many had done so knowingly.
Not surprisingly, those who travel the most are also the most likely to take contraband goods past security – knowingly or unknowingly.
But as the company that conducted the survey notes, TSA&#39;s instructions are quite complicated and confusing.
Passengers often do not know which liquids can be taken on the plane and how much.
So it&#39;s no surprise that the majority of TSA seizures are liquids.
For a while, there was also a belief that books were not allowed on the plane.
Liquids can be taken on domestic flights but not on international flights.
