Georgia massacre: Activists re-enact racist lynching in hope of justice
A Ford Mercury car passes the crowd in the small town of Monroe in rural Georgia and continues its journey towards the small Moore&#39;s Ford bridge.
There are four black passengers and a white driver in the car. Four armed men block the road before the car reaches the bridge.
The leader of the group, a middle-aged man in a striped suit, takes a deep breath from his cigar and peers through the windshield.
Passengers are scared.
&quot;Roger, f---u!&quot; the man is full of shit.
&quot;Get out of the car!&quot;
Screams break the silence as a young black man is pulled from the front seat.
Fortunately, this shocking event is only a re-enactment, which was shown on July 22, 2017.
However, the gasps of shock are genuine when the noose is strung around &quot;Roger&#39;s&quot; neck.
Since 2005, human rights organizations have returned to Moore&#39;s Ford Bridge to re-enact the events of 1946. At that time, two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey, were lynched by the Ku Klux Klan.
No one has been charged with the murders.
&quot;It&#39;s baffling that no one has been arrested all these years - even though the killers live among us and many need to know who they are,&quot; says Tyrone Brooks, who is helping organize the re-enactment.
&quot;It is a disgrace to history, but above all it is a burden that weighs on our souls.&quot;
Brooks is a 71-year-old civil rights activist and former Georgia congressman.
For him, the re-staging is a startling call to action. It also reminds the people of Monroe that wrongs have never been righted.
&quot;We want the culprits to be brought to justice. We want things to finally come to an end, and we want to heal and reconcile, but most of all, we want justice,” says Brooks.
&quot;We cannot recover and reconcile until we get justice.&quot;
A coroner covers the body of a victim who died in the Georgia massacre on 27 July 1946.
According to FBI documents obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected in the lynching.
However, no one was charged with the murder.
Although the perpetrators have been free for decades, according to activists, the motives of the lynching have been known to the locals all along: politics and sex.
In 1946, blacks in the state of Georgia were allowed to vote in presidential elections for the first time by a Supreme Court ruling. The Supreme Court issued its decision in April, and elections were held in the summer.
According to the FBI, there was an incident around the time of the election in which a black tenant farmer, Roger Malcom, stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, in a fight that apparently involved Malcom&#39;s wife, Dorothy.
According to Brooks, it was rumored in town that Hester had had an affair with Dorothy and that Dorothy was expecting a child by him.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, influential white landowner Loy Harrison paid Malcom&#39;s $600 bail, in exchange for which he was released from prison.
On the way home Malcom and Dorothy were accompanied by their cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
A mob stopped their car before Moore&#39;s Ford Bridge.
&quot;It has emerged that Harrison ordered and orchestrated the murders,&quot; the FBI report states.
“It is also apparent that there was collusion between state and local authorities. The authorities were complicit in the murders and destroyed the evidence and did not reveal the identity of the witnesses.&quot;
Brooks puts it more succinctly.
&quot;It was suffrage murder,&quot; he says.
&quot;They were murdered because they wanted to send a message to black people that the same thing will happen to them if they intend to vote.&quot;
Cassandra Greene has been directing re-enactments of the Georgia massacre for nearly a decade.
The show is extremely realistic and captivating. It is a description of the shocking racism that many would like to believe has already disappeared from today&#39;s United States.
It&#39;s hard to watch the show, but even harder not to watch it, which according to Greene is the point.
&quot;We don&#39;t want to talk about lynching because we would have to face our own dark sides,&quot; says the director.
&quot;But I can&#39;t have a relationship with you if you don&#39;t hear me or don&#39;t want to hear what I&#39;ve been through.&quot;
Rehearsals for this year&#39;s show began in June. On the first day, about 30 actors – a dozen black and twenty white – gathered to listen to Greene&#39;s routine summary of the performance.
Wade Marbaugh serves as Greene&#39;s assistant director.
He has played the local Ku Klux Klan leader in a re-enactment for years, but the role is always as difficult and repulsive.
&quot;I feel dirty because I&#39;m not myself,&quot; Marbaugh says.
&quot;However, it is important that this side of history is kept on display so that it never happens again.&quot;
On the other side of the room, Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, aka Roger Malcom and Barnett Hester, practice their turns.
