Average salary 5,300 euros, education whatever - the investment advice situation was &quot;wild and free&quot;
The quality of investment advice has been talking a lot lately.
Most recently, Helsingin Sanomat told about Ritva, 68, to whom the banker&#39;s investment advisor talked a lot while selling investment products.
The rules regarding investment advisors and the sale of various investment products will be tightened at the beginning of next year.
The strictures are based on the new financial market directive, which will be applied from the beginning of next year.
Currently, the evaluation of the skills of investment advisors and employees selling investment products is mainly based on self-regulation.
The law does not specify competence requirements.
The Financial Industry (FA) itself recommends that those working in the investment service complete its own APV1 or APV2 degree.
The financial industry has authorized the organization of the degrees to a company called APV-sijoitustägäut Oy, whose degree working group includes experts from the Financial Supervisory Authority (Fiva), universities and industry players.
The degrees are 12-15 credits in length, and their exams are prepared by Aalto EE, i.e. Aalto University Executive Education Oy, which offers business management development services.
Its website states that, in general, both exams are &quot;quite extensive in terms of requirements&quot;.
The learning material for the degrees includes 10-15 books and numerous other guides and works.
Markku Savikko, the CEO of APV-sijoitustägäut Oy, says that the passing percentage of the exams is roughly estimated to be around 70.
Of the personnel of the largest banks, almost all who provide investment services have completed either the APV1 or APV2 degree, as their completion is mandatory according to the companies&#39; own rules.
Then there are smaller banking firms, without mentioning names, whose personnel seem to have shied away from completing degrees, says Savikko.
According to him, there are &quot;a few&quot; such bankers.
According to Saviko, 13,000-14,000 people have completed the APV1 degree since 2000, and about 3,000 people have completed the more demanding APV2 degrees recommended for investment advisors.
Some banking firms consider having a degree as an advantage.
Several other industries have significantly stricter competence requirements.
Savikko says that the Financial Industry&#39;s recommendation requires the completion of APV degrees, because then the expertise related to the investment industry is ensured.
According to Statistics Finland, financial and investment advisors earn several thousand euros per month on average, including commissions, fringe benefits and performance bonuses.
The average salary for regular working hours of monthly workers is around 5,300 euros.
On average, men working in these positions earn more than 5,900 euros per month, and women earn more than 4,500 euros, respectively.
The top ten earners earn around 8,100 euros on average.
One tenth of the highest earning men earn more than 9,000 euros per month or more, one tenth of the highest earning women earn 6,400 euros or more.
Investment advice according to the Investment Services Act can only be provided by a licensed company.
Until now, self-regulation has been relied on at the employee and task level.
According to Fiva, in its inspection, individual cases were encountered where the investment adviser&#39;s professionalism and qualifications were not sufficient based on the adviser&#39;s activities.
In principle, you can also work as a seller of investment products, even if your skills and qualifications are at a poor level.
Basically, in this respect, the situation has been wild and free.
Several other industries have significantly stricter skill requirements, Savikko states.
According to Saviko, from the beginning of next year, this will be tightened with the new financial market directive (MiFID II).
It requires that each company is responsible for ensuring that the personnel providing investment services are sufficiently competent.
The Financial Supervisory Authority, on the other hand, gets the authority to determine what needs to be done.
Fiva&#39;s market supervisor Marko Hovi says that one of the clear changes to the current one is the regulation on the requirements for the skills and experience of investment advisors and sellers of investment products.
According to Hovi, the new requirements apply to both investment companies&#39; own staff and tied agents who sell products on behalf of a company.
Hovi says that according to the government&#39;s proposal given by the Ministry of Finance, Fiva will have the authority to determine competence and experience.
What exactly they are will probably be decided during the coming autumn.
The company must also in the future take care of the necessary training and, if necessary, follow-up and further training.
This must all be documented, and the company has an obligation to demonstrate that this has also been done.
Hovi clarifies that in practice the company must, for example, map the staff&#39;s job descriptions on an individual level.
There will certainly be different levels of requirements depending on whether it is investment advice or the sale of products.
According to Hovi, the requirement to work with someone more experienced for a certain period of time is also new, if the skills or experience are not at a sufficient level.
That is, if the company hires a new employee who does not quite meet the defined criteria, the employee must work for a certain period with a person who meets the criteria.
According to Hovi, with the change, the rules will become stricter and more specific.
The legislation regarding the sale of investment products will become stricter at the beginning of 2018.
