The results of the new age tests for Swedish asylum seekers were announced
The latest results of medical age tests for asylum seekers in Sweden have been announced. The results of tests carried out using the new evaluation method reveal that more than 80 percent of those tested were determined to be over 18 years old. However, not everyone finds the tests reliable.
Sweden&#39;s National Office of Forensic Medicine began testing earlier this year.
With the tests, the asylum seeker&#39;s age can be assessed more precisely than before. The new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticized for failing to determine the true age of applicants who claimed to be minors.
The Finnish Immigration Service has carried out 6,880 tests so far, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests. The tests were conducted between mid-March and the end of July in 2017.
Of those tested, 80 percent, or 2002 asylum seekers, were determined to be over 18 years old. In addition, the Office of Forensic Medicine determined in 25 cases that the test subject was &quot;possibly 18 years of age or older&quot;.
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker is &quot;possibly under the age of 18&quot;.
Tests were only performed in cases where there was reason to doubt the age stated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson from the Office of Forensic Medicine says that the results are consistent with the results of previous months.
&quot;The figures are quite consistent. There are no big differences from the previous months&#39; statistics,&quot; he told The Local magazine.
Although a large number of applicants were determined to be over 18 years of age, it does not necessarily mean that the applicants lied about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and announced that in 442 cases there were &quot;indications that the subject is 18 years of age or older.&quot;
When Svenska Dagbladet investigated the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases the applicant had openly said that he would turn 18 this year.
In the medical age assessment method used in the tests, x-rays are taken of the wisdom teeth and magnetic images of the knee joints. The images are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists. The method has also been criticized.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose work includes assessing people&#39;s biological maturity. With the evaluation, it can be determined whether the person reached puberty earlier or later than usual.
&quot;I have had reason to think about it, and I am of the opinion that the method used is not the right one.
Determining biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can&#39;t determine the age with certainty, we shouldn&#39;t pretend we can,” he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: &quot;In general, you can say that the risk of determining a child as an adult is small.
The risk is greatest in a situation where the subject will soon turn 18. Then the risk is about 10 percent.&quot;
