How football&#39;s financial rules affect Neymar&#39;s move to Paris
Regulations limiting the use of money by European football clubs do not prevent Neymar&#39;s transfer from Spain&#39;s Barcelona to France&#39;s Paris Saint-Germain. It is the most expensive player transfer ever in football.
Its possible sanctions against Paris Saint-Germain (PSG) will be decided by European football governing body UEFA, which can prevent teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
In 2011, UEFA introduced the financial rules of fair play. According to them, PSG must be able to demonstrate that Neymar&#39;s transfer has been financed without major losses.
Barcelona was paid 222 million euros for terminating the Brazilian&#39;s contract, and Neymar&#39;s annual salary at the new club is in the tens of millions of dollars.
Neymar&#39;s transfer to France involves many financial aspects.
PSG will have no problem paying Neymar&#39;s transfer fee and adding him to their star guard, as the club is funded by Qatar&#39;s oil-rich ruling family.
Clubs are allowed to spend large sums of money to acquire players, but they must be balanced with real sources of income so that football-related business is not loss-making.
The financial rules of fair play were drawn up on the initiative of the Frenchman Michel Platini, who was elected UEFA president in 2007.
As a former footballer, Platini believed that pursuing success through debt was cheating and would lead to serious problems if the banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, the focus of the financial rules of fair play shifted from clubs&#39; debts to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the implementation of the business model first used by Roman Abramovich at Chelsea in 2003 became significantly more difficult. Abramovich bought a promising team, spent huge sums on player acquisitions and created a global brand.
The current three-year review period for the Financial Fair Play Rules runs until 2018. During that time, the clubs are allowed to make a maximum loss of 30 million euros.
Although Platini had to leave the position of UEFA president amid scandal in 2015, his successor Aleksander Ceferin also wants to curb the clubs&#39; reckless spending of money.
&quot;The rules of fair play are still in use, and we will also apply them in the future,&quot; Andrea Traverso, who is in charge of financial rules of fair play at UEFA, told the Associated Press news agency last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar out of his contract with a one-time payment, it can amortize the amount in the accounts for the entire duration of his new contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer amount can be recorded as an annual expense of 44.4 million euros for the next five years.
Based on the economic rules of fair play, the first sanctions were handed out in 2014. The biggest sanctions were imposed on PSG and Manchester City, which is financed from Abu Dhabi.
PSG was fined 60 million euros, which was later reduced to 20 million euros. In addition, the club was ordered to limit its Champions League squad to 21 players for the 2014–15 season instead of the usual 25 players.
UEFA is monitoring clubs that may try to circumvent its financial regulations by increasing their income through companies linked to the club&#39;s owners.
If, for example, a Qatari company supports PSG, but the value of the support is considered to be higher than the usual level of the market, UEFA does not count the support as actual income.
That&#39;s what happened when UEFA decided in 2014 that Qatar&#39;s tourism authority&#39;s support for PSG was excessive.
It has also emerged that some of Neymar&#39;s earnings at PSG could be funded by fees available from the organizing committee for the 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar.
However, PSG and the organizing committee have denied that Neymar is being made an ambassador for the World Cup. It would be very easy for UEFA to expose such an arrangement.
Due to PSG&#39;s previous sanctions, UEFA is following even more closely than usual attempts to circumvent the rules.
Sources familiar with the situation said on Thursday that UEFA has not negotiated with PSG regarding Neymar&#39;s transfer.
The sources gave an interview to the Associated Press news agency on the condition that their identities not be revealed because they are not authorized to discuss the situation at PSG.
According to the latest published financial statements, PSG&#39;s turnover in the 2015–2016 season was 542.4 million euros and the operating profit was more than 10 million euros.
Last season&#39;s financial statements have not yet been announced.
PSG expects Neymar&#39;s arrival to attract new sponsors and boost sales of club merchandise and jerseys.
The club estimates that its turnover will increase by at least 30 percent with Neymar&#39;s contract.
The Spanish league, clearly irritated by the departure of one of the best players in the world, tried to make Neymar&#39;s transfer difficult. It was argued that it violated the financial rules of fair play.
&quot;This is a clear financial doping case for both the club and the state,&quot; Spanish league president Javier Tebas told the Spanish AS newspaper. With the state, he referred to PSG&#39;s Qatari ownership.
Arsenal&#39;s manager Arsene Wenger also has reservations about the state financing the football club&#39;s operations. Arsenal is owned by an American sports tycoon.
&quot;The case is the result of an ownership that has completely changed the operating environment of football over the last 15 years,&quot; Wenger said on Thursday.
&quot;Everything is possible after the state owns the football team.
Adherence to financial rules of fair play becomes very difficult. There are so many different interests related to the fact that a famous player represents the state.&quot;
