Small Circle Nostalgia: Wet Hot American Summer and Comrade Detective
The story simultaneously longs for the characters&#39; glory days in the 80s and the grunge of the 90s (around the time David Wain and Michael Showalter made the excellent The State sketch series for MTV) and its own time - the year 2001, before Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler, Paul Rudd and the other stars of the series moved on to bigger things in their careers.
As a cultural product, it is both a parody and a description of the constant reminiscence we are stuck with in the Facebook era.
As a commercial product, it feels out of date.
First Day of Camp worked surprisingly well, and not just because of its absurd humor (it, among other things, told the backstory of a vegetable can that speaks with the voice of H. Jon Benjamin).
The core of the joke is that the middle-aged Actors play lusty teenagers approaching adulthood. Emphasizing it makes the impossibility of reaching the past part of the joke.
Ten Years Later, in which adults play adults, is less emotionally based and its parody is more fragmented: it parodies, for example, 90s stalker flicks, such as the horror film The Hand That Rocks the Cradle.
At one point, one of the characters digs out an Apple Powerbook, inline roller skates and &quot;other stuff from 1991&quot;.
Many of the stories are the same as before.
Good-hearted Coop (Michael Showalter) is now a writer but still hasn&#39;t gotten over Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) is still a virgin.
And one crazy plot involves Ronald Reagan (aka Michael Showalter) as his accomplice George HW Bush (played aptly by Michael Ian Black).
As always in series like this, the best part is the side paths.
It&#39;s especially funny to see the ever-young Paul Rudd, who has a beard tassel under his lower lip, i.e. Matt Dillon&#39;s &quot;soul patch&quot; from the movie Singles. Andy, played by Rudd, the king of the camp, is starting to be an old man.
Moments of random insanity might make this series take off as a sort of recursive Seven Up! series until it reaches its obvious conclusion: Wet Hot American Summer – Twenty Years Later. In its final scene, a group of friends go to the premiere of Wet Hot American Summer.
Amazon&#39;s Comrade Detective series, on the other hand, appeals to a different kind of nostalgia: the Cold War spirit of The Americans, the film Atomic Blonde, and even the wrestling imagery of the GLOW series, where East meets West.
The comedy series was created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka and directed by Rhys Thomas. It is made into a Romanian police drama of the 1980s, where a couple from Bucharest fight for truth, atheism and Marxism-Leninism.
Florin Piersic Jr and Corneliu Ulici play the lead roles as hard-faced Gregor and idealistic Iosefi. Their lines have been dubbed into English by Channing Tatum (executive producer of the series) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
That&#39;s a great idea,
but it&#39;s not much else.
The series has some good visual jokes (cops spend their time watching chess on TV the same way Americans watch football).
Featuring a host of famous voice actors, including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloë Sevigny. Their banter makes for a really fun game.
However, Comrade Detective gets too caught up in imitating a clumsy socialist drama – for example, there is a killer hiding behind a Reagan mask. That&#39;s why the series often really starts to feel like clumsy propaganda.
Six long episodes are too long, and the humor in the series is not fast enough or plentiful.
Condensed, the series might work better as an agitprop satire, for example when Gregor and Iosef repeatedly visit the American embassy and there are always two fat men in the lobby munching on hamburgers.
The message to the imagined communist audience is that Western culture can turn everything into consumer goods and fast food.
The fictional Romanian creators of the series were not wrong: we devour our own recent history and their history like a turd.
