The decision-makers of the central bank&#39;s monetary policy committee decided by a vote of 6-2 to keep interest rates at 0.25 percent. The interest rate hike received even less support this month, as economic growth has been lackluster.
In its quarterly inflation review, the bank lowered its 2017 growth forecast to 1.7 percent and its 2018 forecast to 1.6 percent. It also warned that there will be even more pressure on household income levels, as inflation is still expected to accelerate to close to three percent in the fall.
However, according to the bank, interest rate increases are needed in the next few years to curb the inflation accelerated by Brexit. In addition, the bank announced that loan costs may have to be increased more than expected in the financial market.
In addition, the members of the committee decided to cancel part of the massive economic package, which began to be implemented a year ago in the aftermath of the Brexit referendum.
The bank will end the Term Funding Scheme in February 2018, although it is now expected to provide £15m more low-cost funding to banks through the scheme, for a total of £115m.
The following is stated in the minutes of the bank&#39;s interest rate decision: &quot;According to the forecast of the committee responsible for monetary policy, the slow development of the gross domestic product will continue in the next few years, when the decline in real household incomes will reduce consumption.&quot;
With regard to interest rates, the bank reiterated that in order to contain inflation, a &quot;some degree of tightening of monetary policy&quot; is needed &quot;slightly more&quot; than the market&#39;s expectations.
The market is currently predicting the first increase in the third quarter of 2018 and the second in 2020.
However, the bank emphasized that possible increases are &quot;gradual&quot; and &quot;limited&quot;.
In May, the bank predicted 1.9 percent growth for this year and 1.7 percent growth for next year.
Now it kept its 2018 growth forecast at 1.8 percent.
The pound weakened against the dollar and the euro as a result of the news.
Against the dollar, the pound weakened by 0.5 percent and was $1.31. Compared to the euro, it weakened by 0.4 percent and was 1.11 euros.
The decision to keep interest rates unchanged was made after weaker-than-expected growth figures dampened increased expectations for interest rate hikes. GDP grew by 0.3 percent in the second quarter and 0.2 percent in the first quarter.
The bank expects growth to remain at 0.3 percent in the third quarter, but to pick up slightly at the end of the year.
Its most recent inflation survey gave little hope to households suffering from accelerating inflation and meager wage increases. According to the bank, the situation will get worse before it gets better.
The bank added that monetary policy &quot;cannot prevent&quot; the decline in income in the next few years. However, it expects wage growth to recover &quot;significantly&quot; at the end of the three-year forecast period.
The economy will also be strengthened by the strong growth in demand for British products as a result of the weak pound. It cancels out part of the effect of the decline in private consumption.
The decision comes a year after interest rates were cut to 0.25% in the wake of a shock EU referendum result that sent the pound plummeting.
The bank estimates that the overall effects of the decision will probably start to be seen in prices and the economy only after four years.
