NHS to prescribe 10,000 controversial HIV drug
Starting in September, patients can be prescribed a &quot;breakthrough&quot; anti-HIV drug. A dispute over the funding of a drug in England&#39;s public health system (NHS) was settled in the Supreme Court.
The NHS announced that around 10,000 people will be prescribed pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) during the first three-year trial. The medicine taken before intercourse has been found to reduce the risk of infection by about 86 percent in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a High Court ruling last year. It says the NHS is able to pay for PrEP, although it says local authorities should fund it.
Simon Stevens, the head of NHS England, called the decision announced on Thursday a &quot;significant new intervention&quot; and the National AIDS Society described it as a &quot;crucial moment&quot;.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to start accepting applications for the trial, which will expand to other clinics in October. The trial will reach its full scope in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medication taken before intercourse that reduces the risk of infection.
Trials have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infections in at-risk groups.
Taking the medicine before intercourse means that the body has enough medicines during intercourse to prevent HIV infection.
The medicine can be taken daily or two hours before sex.
The target group of treatment includes gay men, bisexual men and transgender people, as well as people with an HIV-positive partner who is not receiving effective treatment.
Clinics select eligible applicants for the trial from men, women and transgender people, as well as those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to be receiving antiretroviral treatment for their disease.
People living in England and registered with a general practitioner can also apply for a trial at their local sexual health clinic.
The program costs £10m and NHS England this week signed a contract for the drugs following an international tender.
The purpose of the trial is to evaluate the potential of the PrEP drug by gathering extensive clinical evidence on its targeting, uptake and treatment implementation.
&quot;This significant new intervention should complement and enhance the already existing diverse and increasingly effective means of preventing HIV,&quot; says Stevens.
&quot;It&#39;s yet another significant achievement in the struggle that has been going on for more than 30 years in solving one of humanity&#39;s greatest health challenges.&quot;
&quot;This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV,&quot; says Deborah Gold, director of the National AIDS Society.
“If PrEP is targeted correctly to those who need it and are at risk, it could have a game-changing impact on the HIV epidemic in England.
