This year, the A Voice for Young Syrian Refugees survey explored the opinions and attitudes of young Syrian refugees living in Jordan and Lebanon.
In February-March 2017, a total of 400 Syrian youth aged 18-24 responded to the survey, half of whom are women and half are men.
Half of the interviews were conducted in Jordan and half in Lebanon.
According to the study, more than half of the young Syrian refugees do not believe that they will return to their homeland permanently in the future.
42 percent of the respondents can think of returning to their home country and four percent could not say.
According to the study, the war going on in Syria and the presence of ISIS in the country have the most influence on the young people&#39;s decision to return home.
Almost half (47%) consider the end of the war to be the factor most influencing permanent return home, while a quarter think the most important thing would be ISIS leaving the country.
Only less than a tenth mention the improvement of the economic situation or the departure of Bashar al-Assad from Syria as the most important factors influencing the decision.
Military action alone will not resolve a conflict
Syrian youth were asked which factor is the most important in terms of ending the conflict.
The majority is of the opinion that the cessation of hostilities is more essential than President Bashar al-Assad&#39;s relinquishment of power.
A good quarter consider al-Assad&#39;s presidency an obstacle to the peace agreement.
Almost half feel that both political and military solutions are needed to end the ongoing Syrian conflict.
Only a quarter believe that the conflict can be resolved through military measures alone.
The majority of young Syrian refugees see that ISIS&#39;s power has weakened over the past year, while a fifth feels that its power has strengthened.
According to the respondents, the most important thing in the fight against ISIS, and terrorism in general, is for the media to convey information to people that ISIS has nothing to do with the Islamic faith.
