The most popular cloud services, such as Amazon&#39;s AWS, Microsoft&#39;s Azure, Alibaba&#39;s Cloud, offer MariaDB to their customers.
At the same time, MariaDB is distributed to new users automatically in the distribution packages of Linux operating systems, where MariaDB has largely replaced MySQL.
Although we are a small company, we have connections with the biggest gamblers.
&quot;Among our customers are the world&#39;s largest telecom operators, gaming companies, banks and even some central banks,&quot; Paqvalén lists.
The database market is still dominated by giants like Oracle, Microsoft, IBM and SAP with their closed databases.
Even for Oracle, MySQL is a modest side business compared to the company&#39;s traditional closed database.
Although, according to the research company Gartner, the largest database companies have lost market share in recent years, in terms of revenue players like MariaDB are still insignificant, if fast-growing companies.
In a database market of about 50 billion dollars, open source databases don&#39;t even reach a billion.
However, the value of open source cannot be measured only in money, because the majority of users do not pay anything for this software.
The research company Gartner predicts that in 2018, companies will already develop more than 70 percent of their internal applications on top of open databases.
In addition, more than half of the old databases would have been changed to open ones at that time, or the transition would have at least started.
Big companies don&#39;t get new customers because most of them choose open source code next.
This has led to skyrocketing license fees for commercial databases.
Companies want to make as much money as before with a smaller number of customers,&quot; Widenius reflects.
Since changing a closed database is difficult, the majority of customer companies have obediently swallowed the price increases.
&quot;There are many customers for whom the transition is really difficult, because their old applications and others are stuck in a closed database,&quot; says Widenius.
He still believes that the measure of customers is getting full.
As the license fees increase every year, sooner or later the customer will switch to an open source database.
