The names of drug dealers, politicians, businessmen and journalists who are suspected to be on the payroll of the government or drug cartels are written on the board. They are the criminals who make reporting on the chaos in Mexico a life-threatening situation.
The violence is unrelenting, and journalists are increasingly being targeted. According to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 journalists have been murdered since President Enrique Peña Nieto took office in December 2012. There are 589 journalists under federal protection who have been attacked and threatened. At least seven journalists have been murdered in seven states this year.
Among the latest victims is Javier Valdez Cardenas, founder, editor and source of inspiration for Riodoce.
&quot;The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,&quot; Valdez wrote in one of his many books on drug violence.
He is deeply missed, even though he is present everywhere. A huge picture of Valdez showing the middle finger covers the facade of the Riodoce building. The picture reads: &quot;Justice&quot;. Journalists Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, in their thirties, are wearing T-shirts emblazoned with Valdez&#39;s smiling face. Valdez wears glasses and a trademark Panama hat.
