In 2010, a federal prosecutor&#39;s office was created specifically to handle journalists&#39; cases, but only two prosecutions have been filed so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
The murderers of journalists are rarely brought to justice, just like the thousands of murders related to drug trafficking and organized crime every year, only a few end up in court.
Riodoce journalists plan to continue writing about the violence in Sinaloa, even though they are grief-stricken and the situation is even more dangerous.
According to Ibarra, the security meeting is of little use because the killers are unknown and there is no hope of justice.
&quot;This meeting is frankly a waste of time,&quot; he says.
&quot;We can&#39;t trust anyone as long as we don&#39;t know the reason for the incident.&quot;
Valdez had left Riodoce delivery in the state capital Culiacan on the morning of May 15, 2017.
He had only driven a couple of blocks in his red Toyota when two men stopped him and forced him out of his car and fired twelve shots. The number is presumably related to the name of the magazine: Riodoce means twelfth river.
The shooter drove away in Valdez&#39;s car and crashed it some distance away.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He was survived by his wife and two adult children.
Rumors move fast and run wild in Culiacan.
However, Valdez&#39;s death is being kept quiet.
Sinaloa has been one of Mexico&#39;s bloodiest battlegrounds since Guzman was arrested last year and deported to the United States in January. Competing factions want to fill the void.
On the streets of Sinaloa, one or more people are shot dead every day, and the cemetery has ornate two-story mausoleums of drug lords larger than many homes.
In a coastal state, it is &quot;peaceful&quot; when only one cartel controls the ports and drug trafficking routes to the United States.
Although Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his job, Riodoce founder and director Ismail Bojorquez, 60, feels guilty for not being able to protect his friend.
He believes two mistakes led to Valdez&#39;s murder.
In February, Riodoce published an interview with Damaso Lopez. He leads a rival faction waging war against Guzman&#39;s sons.
The story might have angered Guzman&#39;s sons: customers suspected of being members of the gang bought every issue of the magazine as soon as it hit the newsstands.
Another mistake was not forcing Valdez to leave the country after another newspaper that published the same story was attacked.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder is considered a turning point in violence against journalists.
He had survived so much that his friends and colleagues could no longer fear for him.
He had a long career in Noroeste when he decided to found Riodoce with five colleagues in 2003. The magazine&#39;s shares were sold for $50 at the time.
In Sinaloa, &quot;it was impossible to do journalism without dealing with the drug problem,&quot; says Bojorquez.
Over time, the magazine became known for its brave and honest stories, and its sales and advertising revenue grew.
Journalists appreciated the opportunity to publish hard-hitting investigative journalism without fear of censorship, and readers were fascinated by stories in the magazine that no one else dared to publish.
Eight years after its founding, Riodoce won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Award for its coverage of Latin America.
That same year, Valdez received the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists for his courage in relentlessly following the story of the Mexican drug trade.
