&quot;I want to be able to move on with my life,&quot; he said after receiving the award from the Committee to Protect Journalists.
Drug trafficking is a &quot;way of life&quot; in Sinaloa, Valdez said in an interview with Rompeviento TV last October.
&quot;The reporter has to accept the task that falls to him - or play stupid.
I don&#39;t want anyone to have to ask me where I was when death was being sown here – why didn&#39;t I tell them what was going on?”
Riodoce&#39;s staff misses Valdez - a jokester who cursed like a dockworker. They miss a friend who always gave them a hug and advice. They need a teacher who knew how to survive.
They trusted his routines.
He always wore a Panama hat.
He went to the El Guayabo bar opposite the delivery and always sat at the same table.
Now they ask if the routines were his destiny.
The death of a colleague has also made them think about how they can best do their work and stay alive.
&quot;Criminals don&#39;t like it if we cover their wives and children and their clean business operations, their secret drug-trafficking runways in our stories.
They were left out of the stories,&quot; says Bojorquez.
At best, it meant strong self-censorship and self-protection,
trusting one&#39;s instincts.
If you feel that everything is not right, you should stay away.
