It had been months since reporters had visited the mountainous countryside controlled by drug gangs.
For this week&#39;s issue, Riodoce&#39;s editor planned three main stories.
Boxing great Julio Cesar Chavez&#39;s brother had been killed in Sinaloa.
The newspaper also intended to reveal that the government&#39;s spending was concentrated in the governor&#39;s hometown.
Also, in one of the most expensive restaurants in Culiacan, just a block away from the prosecutor&#39;s office, a group of people had been kidnapped.
There was no official information about who had been kidnapped and how, so it was necessary to proceed with caution: everyone in the city knew that the restaurant was popular with both drug dealers and the authorities.
