The results of the hard work are now visible.
&quot;If you squint, you could almost believe it was sleeping,&quot; says science writer Caleb Brown, who works as a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Museum.
&quot;It will go down in the history of science as the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs, one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaurs.
Studies of the skin revealed that meat-eating dinosaurs were likely a significant threat to this herbivore, even though it had armor and resembled a walking tank.
Its red-and-white armor camouflaged it from predators, and it was also protected by the darker coloration above and lighter below, which is still present in many animals.
According to experts, it was thus better able to blend in with its surroundings and avoid its enemies, the larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old nodosaurus hit the headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Palaeontological Museum.
The researchers have named it Borealopeta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell. Mitchell was part of the team that took more than 7,000 hours to unearth the dinosaur.
Nodosaurus is so remarkably well preserved that Mitchell and an international team of researchers have been able to determine the patterns and shape of its body scales and armor.
They found that it was protected by a coloration still common in the animal world, where the body is darker on top and lighter underneath.
The discovery was still a surprise because the Borealopeta is significantly larger than modern animals with similar coloration.
It can be concluded that meat-eating dinosaurs preyed on it to such an extent that evolution favored hiding rather than fighting as a means of survival.
Among the current animals, for example, deer, zebras and armadillos have similar coloring. They are significantly smaller and therefore easier prey, which suggests that the nodosaurus was also seriously threatened.
&quot;Predation by a large, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous Cretaceous dinosaurs were,&quot; says Brown.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in Nodosaurus&#39; scales reveals that its skin was reddish-brown.
Scientists are continuing to study the nodosaurus in order to draw conclusions about its life. Among other things, they examined the contents of its gut to find out what it ate at its last meal.
