How did one activist learn to answer the question: to whom do the streets belong?
Brittany Ferrell was deeply shocked on August 9, 2014.
He had arrived in New York the day before from his home in St. Louis and was sitting on the bed of his airbnb apartment browsing Facebook on his phone.
That&#39;s when he noticed a message from a high school friend:
&quot;The police just killed an 18-year-old, and his body is still in the street.&quot;
Confused, he noted that no one else had posted the same information on his feed. That&#39;s why he closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
His timeline had numerous retweets from @TheePharoah.
The username belongs to the St. Louis-based rapper who tweeted in real time about the death of Michael Brown. Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man, had been shot by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
The user in question had also posted a picture of Brown&#39;s lifeless body on the street, where it was left for four hours.
“This is incredible,” Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to him and his community.
He put his phone away. When he returned to Twitter later that evening, there were reports of people gathering on Canfield Drive.
Users posted photos of police cordons and people screaming, as well as a man claiming to be Brown&#39;s father holding a sign that read: &quot;Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!&quot;
Ferrell followed live video footage of a police officer standing in front of protesters with a barking dog.
He says he also saw a video in which another officer cocked his rifle and yelled, &quot;I&#39;m going to kill all of you... animals.&quot;
&quot;This is not normal,&quot; Ferrell remembers saying.
&quot;It was not the kind of murder that we are already used to and that could be called typical.
Then I felt cold shivers.
I was angry and I cried.”
He booked a return flight home for the next day.
The plane landed at eleven in the evening. Ferrell picked up his six-year-old daughter from her father and decided they would leave for Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years has been the subject of a documentary called &quot;Whose Streets?&quot;. It premiered in cinemas on August 11, 2017.
The film is a story of survival and expression, love and loss, strength and perseverance from the perspective of the local people who took to the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell drove toward Ferguson with his daughter, who was wearing a floral dress and matching crown, they had another conversation about &quot;what it&#39;s like to live as a black person and in what circumstances.&quot; They had talked about it countless times before that morning.
&quot;Remember when I told you how black people have had to fight for the things they believe in?&quot; Ferrell remembers telling his daughter.
&quot;We&#39;re going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and that&#39;s not right.&quot;
&quot;I couldn&#39;t help but take my daughter with me,&quot; Ferrell later said.
“The events of today are... the culmination of the events of the past.
My daughter has a right to know that and grow up with it.
He needs to get the skills for activism and organizing, but he also needs to know the different layers and conditions of the experience of living as a black person. And he needs to know what we have to do to be free, to free ourselves.
Although I&#39;ve thankfully been able to protect her from blatant racism, she&#39;s still just like any other black girl.
I feel like I would be harming him if I shielded him from reality.”
Their first stop in Ferguson was South Florissant Road, across from the police station. It became a camp site for activists as they waited for word on how the case would be handled and eventually learned that the police would not be charged.
From there, Ferrell and her daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who was making packed lunches.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to the protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to approach activism in a new way.
&quot;My activism changed completely after August 9,&quot; he says. While studying at the University of Missouri in St. Louis, Ferrell was president of the Minority Nursing Student Association. At that time, he focused on food justice and health disparities in black communities.
&quot;I had no experience in organizing.
Somehow it just happened.”
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, the documentary&#39;s assistant director, at an evening protest.
Folayan said he and cinematographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar &quot;simply wanted to tell&quot; what was happening.
A doubt crept into Ferrell&#39;s mind. He asked, &quot;Do you really want to tell what&#39;s going on, or do you want a story that you can exploit?&quot;
The suspicion was based on the countless times that people, usually white, had appeared in the local community who only wanted to profit from its hardships and perseverance.
&quot;We had heard that those born and raised in Ferguson did not have a common voice,&quot; Folayan said in a recent interview. &quot;We wanted to do things differently.&quot;
Folayan had already contacted assistant director Damon Davis, who is known for his activism among death row inmates.
Davis&#39; presence prompted Ferrell to join the project along with six other locals. The film crew followed the events in the years following Brown&#39;s shooting.
“This is not a documentary where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, it&#39;s us speaking,” says Davis.
&quot;The most important thing for me was how the local people are presented in the film, because I am presented in the same way.&quot;
According to Folayan, the intention was not to focus on Ferrell&#39;s experiences, because it was wanted to show that the people&#39;s movement &quot;is not about a charismatic leader but about the community&quot;. However, Ferrell proved to be the most open of the cast.
That&#39;s why the documentary shows surprisingly private aspects of Ferrell&#39;s life, such as falling in love and getting married.
&quot;I felt pretty naked,&quot; Ferrell laughs as he describes what it was like to see the film for the first time.
&quot;But I understood that this work and the humane portrayal of black people requires a certain vulnerability.&quot;
In addition, Ferrell&#39;s story reiterates and re-centers the role of Black queer women in the larger Black Lives Matter movement.
The movement was born on social media (#BlackLivesMatter) after the police had shot the black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012. Two of the three founders of the movement identify with a queer identity.
&quot;Black queer women&#39;s leadership has kept the whole movement going,&quot; says Ferrell. &quot;It&#39;s because we have to constantly fight on many fronts.
Black queer women have had to endure everything.”
Folayan agrees: &quot;The movement is really run by black women, with a lot of queer women among them.&quot;
However, he emphasizes that Ferrell was not chosen for the documentary &quot;on purpose&quot; because of his queer identity.
&quot;He got the energy going,&quot; says Folayan.
&quot;However, it is no coincidence that he was on the front line. Black queer women live at the intersection of many things, and they have a lot at stake.
His energy is transmitted from the screen.&quot;
News crews have long since left Ferguson, but tensions between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell still has two and a half years left on parole. He was convicted of blocking a highway during a protest.
His description of the socio-political atmosphere in his home corner is short and concise: &quot;A mess.&quot;
Yet he still relies on a slogan he learned by heart on the streets of Ferguson three years ago:
&quot;Our duty is to fight for our freedom.
Our duty is to win.
We must love and support each other.
We can only lose our chains.”
Fitting Likeness: Artist Creates Portraits of Chelsea Manning&#39;s DNA
In the Fridman gallery in New York, faces are hung in the middle of the exhibition space - white, black and brown faces, between which, on closer inspection, you can see similarities.
These 30 works are portraits made by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg based on DNA samples taken from Chelsea Manning&#39;s cheek and hair.
