Dewey-Hagborg analyzed Manning&#39;s DNA algorithmically and created 30 portraits based on his genetic information. They are a sharp, if somewhat theoretical, stance on the editability of DNA data, the ambiguity and the cause-and-effect relationships behind the interpretations, as well as identity.
Chelsea Manning, whose birth name is Bradley Edward, has openly said that she has identified with women since adolescence. In 2013, he was found guilty of 20 crimes, including violating the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
There was only one photo of Manning, who was sentenced to prison: a grainy, black-and-white selfie of a distressed Manning sitting in the driver&#39;s seat of a car. She wears a platinum blonde wig, which became her trademark.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg had behind her the highly popular Stranger Visions project, which she realized in 2012.
In it, he created portraits based on forensic information. He obtained DNA data from, for example, cigarette butts and chewing gum and created images of what the people in question might have looked like.
Then the artist received an email from Paper Magazine.
&quot;They were interviewing Chelsea Manning and needed a picture for their story,&quot; Dewey-Hagborg said at a press conference for the new exhibit.
Manning could not be visited or photographed in prison. So the magazine contacted Chelsea and asked if she would be interested in doing a DNA portrait of Manning.
The artist and his imprisoned muse unexpectedly became pen pals. They wrote to each other for a couple of years.
They even did a Suppressed Images comic book together, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo. It depicted a future where the president would have commuted Chelsea&#39;s sentence and she would be able to watch the show.
In reality, Obama commuted Manning&#39;s sentence just days after the comic book was published. It was a lucky coincidence after seven tough years spent in a Kansas military prison.
It&#39;s also impressive that the exhibition is opening right now, when Donald Trump is waging his own war against whistleblowers and transgender soldiers, finding ever new ways on Twitter to reinforce the powerful divisions he was supposed to be mitigating.
Dewey-Hagborg believes that &quot;everything has a purpose&quot;.
On the gallery wall is an artist&#39;s statement, and beneath that is Manning&#39;s large autograph, with a heart as the dot of the last name&#39;s i. In his statement, the artist demands an end to the &quot;automatic division on which gender, race, sexuality and culture have been based&quot;.
On the opposite wall is Manning&#39;s DNA sequence: a long string of C&#39;s, G&#39;s and A&#39;s written in pencil.
With this combination of 200 letters – or nucleotides, as the artist uses the scientific definition – Dewey-Hagborg wants to illustrate how similar we all are, at least in our biology.
&quot;I hope my exhibition will help people understand that we are equal in terms of our genetic heritage and that genetic information is very personal and open to interpretation,&quot; says Dewey-Hagborg. The exhibition also features his video work Spurious Memories from 2007.
&quot;DNA tells countless stories. 30 of them are on display here.”
The last work in the exhibition is in its own room: a page from Manning and Dewey-Hagborg&#39;s comic book.
In it, Manning&#39;s character rises from prison like King Kong, holding a megaphone.
&quot;If they silence you, they&#39;ve won,&quot; the image reads.
&quot;Never be silent.&quot;
&quot;The text is from a letter I received from Manning,&quot; says the artist from Philadelphia.
&quot;It&#39;s so impressive that I still get chills.&quot;
Contrary to what was portrayed in the comic book, Manning has yet to see the show. When Manning arrives, he is greeted by faces based on his own genetic information like a crowd of protesters in the middle of an exhibition space.
It&#39;s intentional, like everything else in this exhibit: for example, Manning&#39;s DNA sequence is written in pencil at a height equal to his height (157.5 cm).
&quot;The faces were previously on the wall, but I wanted to give them the feeling of a crowd,&quot; says Dewey-Hagborg.
&quot;I wanted to portray the mass movement created by Chelsea, which was also behind her release.&quot;
