The program can be used to make quick polls and votes for certain teams. In addition, you can use it to create a map that shows at a glance which departments the employees are most dissatisfied with and which managers have received the lowest ratings. Based on these, Errett has been able to drill down to the core of the problems.
Companies have realized that they need to monitor workplace culture to avoid becoming the next Uber. The transportation company has been in turmoil since a former employee wrote on his blog about a culture where employees are harassed and those who speak up are punished.
For startups like Glint, such omissions are an attractive business opportunity.
Corporate governance, regulation and compliance is a global industry that could reach over $118.7 billion by 2020, according to the Let&#39;s Talk Payments website.
Based in Denver, Colorado, Convercent is a startup that helps companies detect and prevent inappropriate behavior. Interest in the company grew earlier this year when Uber&#39;s reputation took a hit.
Convercent has almost 600 customers, which include, for example, Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
It recently signed a deal with Uber as well.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to conduct customized surveys, collect responses confidentially in real time, and map out problem areas.
In addition, employees can report inappropriate behavior anonymously by text message.
And if there is reason to suspect the manager of improprieties, the complaints go directly to the company&#39;s board.
&quot;Public opinion has superseded the authorities,&quot; says Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
He reminds that if a company treats its employees badly or acts unethically, the consequences can be expensive, even if the authorities do not intervene. Consumers may start boycotting the company, and it may also lose employees and be sued.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant chain has more than 25,000 employees in 500 locations. The company has been using Convercent for more than a year because it wants to make sure that employees are aware of operating principles and procedures and can easily contact the head office.
Previously, the practice was that if an employee wanted to report a problem, they first had to find out a phone number or email address that could be used to report to the head office. Then he had to file a formal complaint and hope it would be taken seriously.
&quot;It was often a scary and unpleasant experience,&quot; says James Vitrano, general counsel of Ruby Tuesday. According to him, it was difficult to follow up on complaints made by employees.
In the past, problems remained hidden from managers working in another city or state. Now problems like discrimination, harassment and unfair wages can be detected and dealt with more quickly.
&quot;I get an even more comprehensive and comprehensive understanding of the employee&#39;s reality,&quot; says Vitrano, who heads Ruby Tuesday&#39;s risk management group.
&quot;At the same time, we protect our shareholders from lawsuits related to employment relationships.&quot;
According to Quinlan, companies began to take ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to unethical practices during the Enron scandal.
It was only with the advent of social media that companies realized that they could no longer prevent their dirty laundry from being aired publicly.
&quot;Hope was used as a strategy before technology came to control ethics,&quot; says Quinlan.
Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, which is billed regularly.
It is a business model and opportunity accepted by venture capitalists. Both Glint and Convercent are backed by venture capitalists.
In February, Convercent raised $10 million in funding from the likes of Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital. It has raised a total of $47 million in capital.
Glint received EUR 10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and has raised a total of USD 60 million in funding.
The rankings come as no surprise given the connections between companies, corporate culture and venture capital.
According to several studies, employees expect more from their jobs than before.
In a competitive market like Silicon Valley, good salaries and interesting projects are just the beginning.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and valued and that they are giving their time to a genuinely useful company.
&quot;Employees are more committed to the company&#39;s success if they feel comfortable in the company and feel that they are listened to and that their work is rewarding,&quot; says Nina McQueen, director of employee rewards and well-being at LinkedIn.
Investors get returns when companies succeed. Companies succeed when employees are engaged.
Third-party analytics tools promise to boost employee engagement, so it&#39;s no wonder they&#39;re attracting investors.
According to workplace culture experts, knowledge about employee commitment is important,
but it is useless if it is not acted upon.
If a company asks its employees for feedback, it can be seen as a sign of change.
And if change doesn&#39;t come quickly enough, or nothing changes at all, disappointment can reduce employee engagement.
&quot;If you ask for four thousand proposals, you have to be prepared to have four thousand conversations,&quot; says Russell Raath, CEO of management consulting company Kotter International, who has seen companies rely too much on just gathering information.
&quot;If the company doesn&#39;t take action, employees start to wonder if they were heard
and whether their opinions matter.
If the company doesn&#39;t care about them, why should they care about the company?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed now conducts staff surveys on a monthly basis and is able to address a problem the same day it is reported to Glint.
After collecting feedback from employees frustrated with the slowness of decision-making and the quality of communication, Errett was able to make changes to the teams and organize communication training to solve the problems.
Ruby Tuesday understands its employees even better and hopes that deeper understanding will help it improve long-term staff retention in an industry known for high employee turnover.
&quot;If a company does not commit to creating a culture of transparency, it will lose employees,&quot; says Vitrano.
&quot;If it loses employees, it also loses customers.
And without customers, there are no companies.&quot;
