The birth of a comic book: The story of a castle
The small Scotney Castle in Kent is now known for the Squeeze music video and Margaret Thatcher&#39;s hideout from the 1970s and 1980s.
However, it has 700 years of turbulent history behind it. Now this charmingly situated castle in the valley of the river Bewl is the subject of a comic book written by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired writer with a penchant for old documents.
&quot;I think it&#39;s great to be able to study a text written by a person who died more than 300 years ago,&quot; says Rhodes wistfully.
&quot;I feel a personal connection when I hold the letter in my hand.&quot;
Rhodes&#39; book, A Castle in England, tells the stories of the families who lived in Scotney from the Middle Ages to Edwardian times. Each story is illustrated by a different artist, a promising British cartoonist: Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer or Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes&#39; first book based on archives. In 2014, he published Dead Men&#39;s Teeth and Other Stories, whose sources of inspiration were the documents of the British National Library. The project was sensitive.
&quot;I was moved to tears when I noticed a thumbprint in the letter. The letter was written by a double agent who worked for the Jacobites in the 18th century,&quot; says Rhodes.
“It was his fingerprint!
And the letters smell like smoke, because at that time fire was used as lighting.
Three centuries later, the scent makes the reader feel like he is there himself.
I love archives!”
The writer, fascinated by old documents, was able to live in the castle for almost four months with the support of the National Trust and the National Arts Council of England, which seemed too good to be true. He admits that he couldn&#39;t bear to stay in the castle a little longer than expected.
He spent his days exploring the Victorian &quot;new&quot; castle, archives, treasures and rarities such as hyena heads hung on the walls and bottles that had been in the moat for centuries.
He toured the ruins of the old castle and chatted with the forest rangers, gardeners and sometimes also the artists who illustrated the book.
In the evenings, he &quot;took a whiskey and started writing&quot;.
Scotney&#39;s closer history is fairly unknown, as the castle was not fully transferred to the National Trust until the death of the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the foundation&#39;s staff was just starting to go through the archives. Rhodes describes that the archives had been kept for hundreds of years using the same method: taking all the excess to the attic.
The archives contained diaries, letters from the days of the English Empire, and maps of who owned what. &quot;You&#39;d think that land disputes are boring,&quot; says Rhodes. &quot;Here, however, families would even fight over a single birch tree.
It occurred to me that we shouldn&#39;t just let it be.&quot;
Some of the stories in the book progress from the castle to English history, such as The Labourer. It tells the story of a man who joins the English peasant revolt in 1381 shortly after the castle was completed.
&quot;The Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex mentions that there was a riot in the castle in 1380,&quot; says Rhodes.
&quot;The peasant revolt in England started in the same area, and it occurred to me that a revolt can start with a riot.
Maybe these events are connected?”
Other stories in the book are closely related to the history of the castle - such as The Priest, the story of a priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
The Smuggler, on the other hand, tells the story of smuggler Arthur Darrell from the 18th century. He is said to have staged his own funeral by filling the coffin with stones (this was discovered years later when his grave was opened).
The Darrells are Rhodes&#39; favorite family in Scotney. &quot;The men in the family seem to have been quite scoundrels. They kept going into debt and buying things they couldn&#39;t have afforded.
The men in the Darrell family solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy old women. I see them as handsome guys who knew how to seduce an heiress.&quot;
Now Rhodes is looking for new writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in Finland writing a comic book about Elämänmäki, a sanatorium that operated at the beginning of the 20th century, of which only a lush plot remains.
Scotney Castle holds a special place in his heart.
&quot;It was sad to leave there,&quot; he says.
&quot;I wouldn&#39;t have wanted to go back to this evil everyday life.&quot;
