Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like nightmares for your digestive system.
However, a recent study claims the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable condition that affects around 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 people in the UK. It causes abdominal cramps, bloating, frequent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
People with irritable bowel syndrome are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at the University of Washington discovered that tryptophan, an essential amino acid contained in protein, helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen the intestinal tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, the leader of the study, immune cells guard the intestine and ensure that harmful microbes hidden in food do not enter the body.
Cells that cause inflammation are balanced by cells that strengthen tolerance. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to inflammation, the result can be irritable bowel syndrome.
In the experiments, it was found that mice with certain bacteria in their intestines have immune cells that strengthen tolerance.
The bacterium in question needs tryptophan so that immune cells start to appear. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
&quot;We found a connection between Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and the development of cells that promote tolerance. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal microbiome of the intestine,&quot; says Professor Colonna.
&quot;The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more immune cells they had.&quot;
If the same works in humans, the combination of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce inflammation sensitivity.
Studying immunity-boosting immune cells, researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that while one group of mice had such cells, mice of the same species that were kept separate from the other group did not.
He suspected that the difference was related to the mice&#39;s gut microbiomes, or the normal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the mice&#39;s gut DNA was examined, six species of bacteria were found that were present in the mice with immune cells, but not in the other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria were given to mice raised in a sterile environment with no gut microbiome and no immune cells developed, they began to develop immune cells.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system. They grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in liquid and transferred small amounts of liquid – without bacteria – to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells developed into cells that strengthen tolerance.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice&#39;s diet, the number of cells that strengthen endurance increased by about 50 percent. When the amount of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells halved.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same immune-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tracts.
It is not yet known whether tryptophan byproducts from Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria cause cells to develop in the same way in humans as in mice. However, genetic defects related to tryptophan have been found in people with irritable bowel syndrome.
&quot;We probably want to promote the development of such cells, because they regulate the inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines,&quot; says Cervantes-Barragan.
&quot;The high level of tryptophan combined with Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria may contribute to their proliferation.&quot;
