The White House exhibit cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House&#39;s decision last month to fly a Navy helicopter onto the South Lawn of the White House for an event showcasing American manufacturing cost taxpayers $24,000. The information appears in military documents obtained by TIME magazine.
The green and white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter is called Marine One when the president is aboard. It was the highlight of an event held at the White House on July 17, 2017, where American construction programs were presented.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and a host of White House officials toured products from all 50 states.
In addition to a helicopter made in Connecticut, the exhibits included a sailboat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
The White House military office had requested the helicopter to the scene with a mission-specific order just about 36 hours before it was due to land on the South Lawn for an &quot;extraordinary&quot; event. This is evident from the documents of the Navy&#39;s HMX-1 helicopter squadron.
&quot;I just wanted to make sure you are aware of the matter because it is an extraordinary event that is getting a lot of visibility,&quot; the commander of the HMX-1 unit wrote in an email the day before the event to his superior, who is the Deputy Commandant of Naval Aviation.
The message said that the helicopter would arrive at the southern grass field on July 17. at seven in the morning and the event would start at three in the afternoon. The helicopter would leave the scene only after the grass field was cleared between six and nine in the evening.
In addition, the message mentioned that if the helicopter&#39;s departure from the White House was delayed, another crew would be needed due to service time restrictions.
The original crew was on board the helicopter during the incident, and unit security personnel were with the helicopter while it was on the ground.
From the documents obtained by TIME magazine, it is not clear whether a second crew was needed in the end.
The US Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
According to the documents, HMX-1 inquired whether the event violated the law.
“One of our questions was whether there was a violation of the Hatch Act. We were told not to break,&quot; the commander wrote.
&quot;Sounds like you can participate,&quot; the deputy commandant replied.
Made in America was an official White House event, so it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president spoke in favor of the health care reform that was being considered by the Senate at the time, as well as looser state regulation.
The use of Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents must wear them when they travel,
but using them only for photographs is unusual.
Trump&#39;s actions drew attention in February when Air Force One taxied into the background of the president&#39;s campaign event in Melbourne, Florida. Trump has strongly criticized his predecessor&#39;s use of the presidential plane on Twitter.
&quot;The White House is very pleased with the Made in America event, which showcased products made by American workers from American materials in all 50 states,&quot; said White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews regularly conduct training flights in the Washington area and practice on the South Lawn bringing the president to the White House to within centimeters.
While Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 practice landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flights to the Made in America event were part of the crew&#39;s monthly training quota.
On that day, the unit&#39;s helicopters were also flown for 11 hours in &quot;non-presidential support missions&quot;.
According to the White House, the event caused no other costs to taxpayers.
Sikorsky&#39;s spokesperson said that the company was not involved in organizing the presentation of the helicopter on the south lawn of the White House.
HMX-1 has no records of flights related to the president&#39;s duties, and an accurate estimate of the event&#39;s expenses is difficult.
According to the Department of Defense&#39;s 2017 hourly compensation, the compensation level for the VH-3D helicopter is $24,380 per flight hour.
According to HMX-1 documents, flights from the Quantico base in Virginia to the White House and back took a total of one hour.
According to the White House, the operating costs of the helicopter are clearly lower.
&quot;Calculating the costs to taxpayers according to the compensation level is misleading,&quot; says Walters.
&quot;The estimated compensation level includes personnel, maintenance and many other so-called sunk costs that are taken into account in the annual appropriations.&quot;
According to a 2015 study by the research firm RAND, compensation levels do not include personnel costs, but do take into account fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
Around the time of the event, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter at the event.
&quot;The idea is to showcase American production,&quot; Spicer said.
“I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud to be involved in ensuring national security and probably employ hundreds or thousands of people as a result.
And I think, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other defense equipment that many Americans have worked so hard for.
It is completely appropriate to bring it up.&quot;
It is not certain if Trump was in the helicopter during the event, but at least he sat in the driver&#39;s seat of the fire truck.
In the White House, Trump joked to the press about his own Sikorsky fleet.
&quot;I know Sikorsky very well,&quot; the president said. “I have three of them.”
